# SoftOS Enforcement Guardrails

Treat these as blocking constraints, not suggestions.

## Source of truth

- Specs in `specs/**` govern system behavior.
- `workspace.config.json` governs repo routing, runtimes, CI delegation, and compose/deploy metadata.
- `.flow/**` is evidence and runtime state only.

## When to stop and read first

Before editing, Cursor must read more context if any of these are true:

- the task touches `flow`, `flowctl/**`, `.github/**`, `scripts/**`, `docs/**`, `workspace.*.json`, or `specs/**`
- the task touches more than one repo
- the task changes CI, release, deploy, stack, or orchestration behavior

In those cases, read:

- `AGENTS.md`
- the relevant spec
- `workspace.config.json`

## File-scope guardrail

- Do not edit files outside the active spec `targets`.
- If the required fix crosses repo or file boundaries not covered by the spec, update or create a spec first.

## Lifecycle guardrail

- Prefer `python3 ./flow spec review|approve`, `flow workflow ...`, `flow ci ...`, `flow release ...`, and `flow stack ...`.
- For workspace-managed toolchains from host, prefer `python3 ./flow workspace exec -- <cmd>` or `scripts/workspace_exec.sh <cmd>` over running runtime binaries directly on the host.
- For repo runtime commands, prefer `python3 ./flow repo exec <repo> -- <cmd>` over `workspace exec` when the repo has a dedicated service.
- Do not replace a `flow` lifecycle action with a custom shell sequence unless no `flow` command exists.

## Completion guardrail

Do not present work as complete if one of these still applies:

- spec is still structurally invalid
- spec governance has not been reviewed/approved when required
- relevant CI gates were not run
- release state and frontmatter are inconsistent

## Anti-drift guardrail

- If adding stable surfaces under `flowctl/**`, `scripts/**`, `docs/**`, `templates/**`, or `.github/**`, align the governing spec in the same change when required.
- Do not “just add templates/docs/scripts” without checking drift/spec coverage.
